It seems, therefore, more methodical to explain vel easdem as an interlinear gloss which subsequently found its way into the text. The remark was due to some ancient reader who not unjustly regarded the arguments of the opponents of Aper as virtually identical, they being, indeed, quite of the same mind as to the actuality of the decline of eloquence. Cf. 16 12 nec aequo animo (sc. Aprum) perferre hanc nostram pro antiquo- rum laude concordiam and 1. 14: non enim . . . saeculum nostrum patiar hac vestra conspiratione damnari.
